  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;>&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.tech.common.extend_supp_soa-ibm/guidances/concepts/service_oriented_architecture_956B2631.html&quot; guid=&quot;_xvH6UEo2Ed6D_7XK49c0nw&quot;>SOA&lt;/a> is an architectural paradigm for defining how people, organizations, and systems&#xD;
    provide and use services to achieve results. SoaML, as described in the Object Management Group &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.tech.common.extend_supp_soa-ibm/guidances/whitepapers/soaml_specification_8B377FF3.html&quot; guid=&quot;_FYb84EovEd6D_7XK49c0nw&quot;>specification document&lt;/a>,&amp;nbsp;provides a standard way to architect and model SOA&#xD;
    solutions using the Unified Modeling Language&amp;reg; (UML&amp;reg;). The profile uses the built-in extension mechanisms of UML to&#xD;
    define SOA concepts in terms of existing UML concepts. SoaML can be used with current &quot;off the shelf&quot; UML tools but&#xD;
    some tools might offer enhanced, SOA specific support.&amp;nbsp; For example, IBM Rational Software Architect, Version&#xD;
    7.5.4 and later, offers&amp;nbsp;a built-in SoaML profile and tooling to automate SoaML-based design and development of&#xD;
    service oriented systems.&lt;/font>&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
